    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<h2>for unit test</h2>\n<p>If you need the location of a class called <strong>Coverage.java</strong> located in package <strong>com.acme.api</strong></p>\n<pre class=\"lang-java prettyprint-override\"><code>Class clazz = Coverage.class;\nClassLoader loader = clazz.getClassLoader();    \nString coverageClazzCompiledAbsoluteTargetLocation = loader\n.getResource(clazz.getCanonicalName().replace(&quot;.&quot;, File.separator) + &quot;.class&quot;)\n.getFile().replace(File.separatorChar + &quot;$&quot;, &quot;&quot;);\nSystem.out.println(coverageClazzCompiledAbsoluteTargetLocation);\n</code></pre>\n<p>Result</p>\n<pre><code>/home/Joe/repositories/acme-api/target/test-classes/com/acme/api/Coverage.class\n</code></pre>\n<p><strong>Note:</strong> Since java needs compilation, you cannot obtain the .java location (src/main/java/...). You need to compile .java into .class, so the location if you are using maven, will be inside of <strong>target</strong> folder</p>\n<h2>at runtime: JAR</h2>\n<p>If you build your app as jar, the location of class will be the jar location plus clazz package</p>\n<h2>at runtime: WAR</h2>\n<p>If you build your app as war, the location of class will be the war location (/bin folder in tomcat) plus clazz package</p>\n"
  } ],
